<paragraph id="8BB7368AD85DFFD23CB4FC1E3088FF77" blockId="8.[151,1059,931,1041]" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D09D85DFFD23DEDFC193010F8DE" authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1841" box="[462,559,931,952]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Perilypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D85DFFD23DEDFC193010F8DE" box="[462,559,931,952]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Perilypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SPINOLA was revised in 1977 (EKIS 1977). This work included a key to species. The available 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D09D85DFFD23E50FC7B3119F8B0" box="[627,806,961,982]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Perilypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="967" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D85DFFD23E50FC7B3119F8B0" box="[627,806,961,982]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Perilypus alpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimen keys out to 
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D85DFFD2382FFC7B32CDF895" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">P. caliculus</emphasis>
EKIS, from which 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D09D85DFFD23DE7FC643044F895" box="[452,635,990,1011]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Perilypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="967" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D85DFFD23DE7FC643044F895" box="[452,635,990,1011]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Perilypus alpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by showing a serrated tegminal dome, which is not present in 
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D85DFFD23DEBFC463000FF76" box="[456,575,1019,1041]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">P. caliculus</emphasis>
specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB7368AD85DFFD23CB4FB9B30EEFEB6" blockId="8.[151,1059,1057,1489]" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 6.0 mm; width 2.0 mm. Form: As in 
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD85DFFD23F5CFB9B31EBFF50" box="[895,980,1057,1079]" captionStart="Figs 270-273" captionStartId="95.[151,191,1512,1534]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,224,1495]" captionTargetId="figure@95.[153,1061,196,1495]" captionTargetPageId="95" captionText="Figs 270-273: Habitus; (270) Aphelocerus yoro; (271) Perilypus alpinus; (272) P. apunctus; (273) P. arsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746796" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746796/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Fig. 271</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium bicolorous, lower frons and clypeus yellow, upper frons, and middle epicranium black, sides of epicranium yellow, cranial venter yellow; antenna black; pronotum broadly yellow at sides, with black discal marking that has central yellow spot; pterothorax dark brown; elytra black; legs bicolorous, femora mostly flavotestaceous, infuscated in distal 1/2, tibiae and tarsi black; abdomen dark brown. Head: Interocular depression shallow, crescentic; frontal umbo not prominent; cranium minutely punctate; antenna (
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD85DFFD23CDEFB54336FFE62" box="[253,336,1262,1284]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) moderately serrate, not densely setose, antennomeres gradually increasing in diameter from scape to antennomere 11; eyes finely facetted, eye narrower than frons (EW/FW 25/38). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD85DFFD23E95FA933129FE59" box="[694,790,1321,1343]" captionStart="Figs 179-193" captionStartId="81.[151,191,1359,1381]" captionTargetBox="[167,1032,201,1342]" captionTargetId="figure@81.[152,1058,201,1346]" captionTargetPageId="81" captionText="Figs 179-193: Pronota; 179) Phonius versus; (180) Perilypus arsus; (181) A. nodus; (182) Pyticara frontegalba; (183) Pelonium implacide; (184) Neorthoplera quintana; (185) Perilypus virgulatus; (186) P. alpinus; (187) Amboakis expandosa; (188) Ampleris jatai; (189) Megaphloeus jasuni; (190) Amboakis bermejo (191) Madoniella delta; (192) Megaphloeus imparilus; (193) Pyticeroides brevitubulus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746768" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746768/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Fig. 186</figureCitation>
) transverse, very finely punctate; pronotal arch well defined; subapical depression well defined; side margins of pronotum proper strongly arcuate (PW/PL 90/78); elytra oblong rectangulate, pubescence short and profusely distributed throughout disc; disc punctures small and profusely distributed on disc, epipleural fold plane (EL/EW 240/65). Abdomen: Pygidium transverse 
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D85DFFD23D44FA013351FEB7" bold="true" box="[359,366,1467,1489]" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">/</emphasis>
scutiform; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD85DFFD23E56FA0130EEFEB6" box="[629,721,1467,1489]" captionStart="Figs 207-212" captionStartId="84.[151,191,1256,1278]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,199,1242]" captionTargetId="figure@84.[153,1061,199,1242]" captionTargetPageId="84" captionText="Figs 207-212: Aedeagi; (207) Aphelocerus tigra; (208) A. yoro; (209) Perilypus alpinus; (210) P. apunctus; (211) P. arsus; (212) P. izabal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746774" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746774/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Fig. 209.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB7368AD85DFFD23CB4FA5B32D6FD72" blockId="8.[151,1058,1505,1556]" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">N a t u r a l H i s t o r y: The available specimen was collected during June, by beating.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB7368AD85DFFD33CB4F99E306DFA61" blockId="8.[151,761,1571,1593]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1058,211,263]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="968" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">
